    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-03-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-03-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="828"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d828">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51 Con-Ob American Group/42</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chinese Minister of Finance</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kung</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the American, Ambassador in China</hi>
                        (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="96" xml:id="d828fn96">Copy transmitted to the Department by
                        the Ambassador in his despatch No. 415, April 9; received May 3.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-03-31">March 31,
                            1937</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Ambassador Johnson</hi>: Now that the Hukuang and
                    Chicago Bank loan settlements have been effected I desire to take up the case of
                    the Pacific Development Loan. To this end I should appreciate your transmitting
                    by telegraph, as you recently were good enough to do in the case of the Hukuang
                    and Chicago loans, the attached communication to Mr. Lamont<note n="97"
                        xml:id="d828fn97">Thomas W. Lamont, representing the American group of the
                        China Consortium.</note> of Messrs. J. P. Morgan &amp; Company which
                    contains a proposal of settlement. Also I should appreciate having a copy
                    furnished to the Chinese Ambassador at Washington.</p>
                <p>Yours faithfully,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">H. H. Kung</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
